 Ilonas, the shepherd country, more animal, hill and rock than man.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This was where the marble road leading into the Widelands begun.
 This was where his quest had taken him so far.
 For weeks he had been on the road, suffering fools too gladly sometimes,
 subjecting his body into such a trial of strength of will and body as traveling
 on foot for almost what seemed to be half around the world.
 Indeed a feat in itself, it was simply the means to far greater a prize,
 the complete knowledge of which still eluded him, despite all the years
 of studies and inquiries, both his and his master's.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The marble road started off as a narrow, thin road, small edges of pure
 white marble-like material delineating its boundaries.
 It was not really made from marble, for if it was it would have been demolished
 and chipped away bit by bit long ago.
 But it seems to defy any tool and machination of man, neither pickax nor
 chisel capable of even slightly damaging the road.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sleek, shiny white-gray road, cold to the touch but fine and delicate,
 like glass-work.
 But unbreakable, unyielding, unscathed by time, man, or nature.
 A foreign body so exquisitely crafted that it is indeed unique, and no
 artisans at any time, and no empire that ever rose and fell ever managed
 to construct such a piece of perfection, truly as some poet once said 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

for the Gods to walk upon the lands
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was, and had always been, part of the lands, but alien to them as well.
 The people had always known of the marble road, just as they knew of the
 trees, the mountains and the rivers, the forests and the glens, the fields
 and the wheat, the goat and the cow, the suns and the moon.
 But these things were of nature, and the marble road clearly was not, for
 nature abhors uniqueness.
 Animals come in pairs, rivers abound, so do trees.
 But there is only one marble road.
 A perfect thing; a left over from the time Gods walked among us.
 Or even so, before us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What reason was there behind it? Why does it lead into the Widelands? What
 is it made of? And who made it? With what tools, what materials did they
 use? They, because this must surely be the work of thousands.
 No single man could ever accomplish such a work in his lifetime.
 Perhaps, most rightly so, it is the work of the Gods.
 And to try and unravel their reasoning and purpose can only lead to madness,
 heresy, or both.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Molo decided to leave such thoughts aside, thoughts which beget questions
 that begged for answers he could not find.
 At least not before he ventured into the Widelands proper, until he found
 what Umberth described as the Necropolis, where inestimable knowledge was
 waiting to be uncovered to the world.
 Knowledge of a time unknown, perhaps before man ever walked the lands.
 The Time of the Gods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was already a fascinating sensation, walking upon the very same road
 that even the Gods might have walked upon once.
 What other man, apart from him and Umberth had dared walk the marble road
 unto its terribly unknown end? What other man, who lived long enough to
 tell the tale? What other man, who was not hunted down as a heretic, a
 blasphemer? What other man who didn't have a tragic, miserable end? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He grinned wickedly at these thoughts, for they were immediately followed
 by his aspirations: He wouldn't perish neither in the Widelands, nor at
 the hands of a fanatical mob, or the ever watchful Procrastinators.
 He would not succumb to any torture the Ministers might want to put him
 through for when all his trials and tribulation had come to pass this,
 he would not be simply a man anymore.
 He would not be hunted down, or exiled, or even held at bay, as a feared
 and terrible man.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No, when all the power and majesty and magnificence of the Gods was unveiled
 and made manifest through him, he would be transformed into a being of
 awe and power that the lands had not witnessed since the beginning of time.
 He would become a living deity, an avatar of the Gods, and he would be
 loved, and cherished, and worshiped as a God among men should.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He knew the truth of it, he could feel it in his heart and bones, see it
 in his twisting dreams.
 Dreams of cleansing light and fire, himself a creature of wrath and glory,
 terrible power at his hands and unimaginable purpose in his mind.
 The purpose of the Gods.
 Indeed it was their divine plan.
 Conceived and hatched untold eons ago, and he was their chosen instrument.
 He would not fail them.
 For the lust of that power burned deep withing, deeper than the need for
 breath itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But he had indeed to find the Necropolis first, and that task seemed ever
 so slightly more difficult with each passing day.
